.TH "TEMPORAL.PLAINDATE.DAYSINYEAR" "3JS" "December 8, 2025" "JavaScript" "JavaScript Reference Manual"
.SH NAME
Temporal.PlainDate.daysInYear \- Temporal.PlainDate.prototype.daysInYear
.SH SYNOPSIS
The \f[B]\f[CB]daysInYear\f[B]\f[R] accessor property of
\f[CR]Temporal.PlainDate\f[R] instances returns a positive integer
representing the number of days in the year of this date.
It is calendar\-dependent.
.PP
For the ISO 8601 calendar, this is 365, or 366 in a leap year.
In other calendar systems, it likely differs, especially in non\-solar
calendars.
.PP
The set accessor of \f[CR]daysInWeek\f[R] is \f[CR]undefined\f[R].
You cannot change this property directly.
.SH EXAMPLES
.SS Using daysInYear
.IP
.EX
\f[B]const\f[R] date = Temporal.PlainDate.from(\(dq2021\-07\-01\(dq);
console.log(date.daysInYear); \f[I]// 365\f[R]

\f[B]const\f[R] date2 = Temporal.PlainDate.from(\(dq2020\-07\-01\(dq);
console.log(date2.daysInYear); \f[I]// 366; 2020 is a leap year\f[R]

\f[B]const\f[R] date3 = Temporal.PlainDate.from(\(dq2021\-07\-01[u\-ca=chinese]\(dq);
console.log(date3.daysInYear); \f[I]// 354\f[R]

\f[B]const\f[R] date4 = Temporal.PlainDate.from(\(dq2023\-07\-01[u\-ca=chinese]\(dq);
console.log(date4.daysInYear); \f[I]// 384; 2023 is a Chinese leap year\f[R]
.EE
